1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,900
When you order a meal at a restaurant,

2

00:00:01,900  -->  00:00:03,600
you give your order, and then you

3

00:00:03,600  -->  00:00:06,080
expect that the restaurant will give you something in return.

4

00:00:06,080  -->  00:00:08,220
In this case, your meal.

5

00:00:08,220  -->  00:00:12,860
But what if the restaurant only took in orders but never gave out a meal?

6

00:00:12,860  -->  00:00:15,145
That restaurant wouldn't be around for very long.

7

00:00:15,145  -->  00:00:18,710
In the same way, we need to think about that in our Python code,

8

00:00:18,710  -->  00:00:21,320
and make sure that it returns the output we

9

00:00:21,320  -->  00:00:24,995
expect it to and need it to every single time.

10

00:00:24,995  -->  00:00:29,910
There are two fundamental functions in Python for interacting with the user.

11

00:00:29,910  -->  00:00:33,330
The print function outputs text to the console,

12

00:00:33,330  -->  00:00:37,550
while the input function reads a line of text from the user.

13

00:00:37,550  -->  00:00:39,470
Consider the input function.

14

00:00:39,470  -->  00:00:44,230
When we need a user to supply the function or program with an input,

15

00:00:44,230  -->  00:00:46,515
such as your name or email,

16

00:00:46,515  -->  00:00:48,170
or any other piece of data,

17

00:00:48,170  -->  00:00:50,710
we're going to use the input function to prompt

18

00:00:50,710  -->  00:00:54,650
the user to put in some text via an input box.

19

00:00:54,650  -->  00:00:59,920
In this example, the input function prompts the user to enter their name.

20

00:00:59,920  -->  00:01:02,010
When you're writing Python code,

21

00:01:02,010  -->  00:01:05,270
print statements are incredibly helpful for logging,

22

00:01:05,270  -->  00:01:10,890
and also for tracking what your functions and scripts are doing or maybe not doing.

23

00:01:10,890  -->  00:01:16,110
This way, we can see what our Python program sees immensely

24

00:01:16,110  -->  00:01:21,550
helpful for debugging if we're getting unexpected outputs and need to retrace our steps,

25

00:01:21,550  -->  00:01:23,530
or figure out what's going on.

26

00:01:23,530  -->  00:01:29,190
In this example, the print function outputs a greeting message.
